I wonder if these estimations of integer overflow cost have taken into account all the possible optimizations where the compiler could safely remove overflow checks. For example, consider:<p><pre><code>    void memzero_range(char* array, int start, int end) {
        for(int i = start; i < end; i++)
             array[i] = 0;
    }
</code></pre>
In that example, a sufficiently smart compiler could just check for the `start > end` case once at the start of the loop, and remove the overflow check from the body. Perhaps this is something that today&#x27;s Clang/GCC can already do?
